Bruce Lee (Chinese: 李小龍; born Lee Jun-fan, 李振藩; November 27, 1940 – July 20, 1973) was a Hong Kong and American actor, director, martial artist, martial arts instructor and philosopher.He was the founder of Jeet Kune Do. Lee is considered by critics, media, and other martial artists to be the most influential martial artist of all time and a pop culture icon of the 20th century, who bridged the gap between East and West. 

Born in San Francisco and raised in British Hong Kong, Lee was introduced to the Hong Kong film industry as a child actor by his father. However, these were not martial arts films. His early martial arts experience included Wing Chun (trained under Yip Man), tai chi, boxing (winning a Hong Kong boxing tournament), and apparently frequent street fighting (neighbourhood and rooftop fights). In 1959, Lee, having U.S. citizenship due to his birth, was able to move to Seattle. In 1961, he enrolled in the University of Washington.It was during this time in the United States that he began considering making money by teaching martial arts, even though he aspired to have a career in acting. He opened his first martial arts school, operated out of home in Seattle. After later adding a second school in Oakland, California, he once drew significant attention at the 1964 Long Beach International Karate Championships of California by making demonstrations and speaking. He subsequently moved to Los Angeles to teach, where his students included Chuck Norris, Sharon Tate, and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar. In the 1970s, his Hong Kong and Hollywood-produced films elevated the Hong Kong martial arts films. 

He is noted for his roles in five feature-length Hong Kong martial arts films in the early 1970s: Lo Wei's The Big Boss (1971) and Fist of Fury (1972); Golden Harvest's The Way of the Dragon (1972), directed and written by Lee; and Golden Harvest and Warner Brothers' Enter the Dragon (1973) and The Game of Death (1978).

Time named Lee one of the 100 most important people of the 20th century. #brucelee #longbeach #hollywood #jeetkunedo #wingchun #ipman #martialarts #usa #selfdefense #karate #jkd #fitness #enterthedragon #junfangungfu  #muaythai #mma #instagram #bjj

Edmund Kealoha Parker was an American martial artist, Senior Grandmaster, and founder of American Kenpo Karate. Notable students included Benny Urquidez, Dan Inosanto, Elvis Presley, Chuck Norris. 

Born in Hawaii, Parker began training in Judo at an early age and later studied boxing. During the 1940s, Parker was introduced to Kenpō by Frank Chow, who then introduced Parker to William Chow, a student of James Mitose. Parker trained with William Chow while serving in the Coast Guard and attending Brigham Young University, and in 1953 he was promoted to the rank of black belt. Parker opened the first karate school in the western United States in Provo, Utah, in 1954. By 1956, Parker opened a dojo in Pasadena, California. 

Ed Parker's first black-belt was James Ibrao. Other black belts in chronological order up to 1962 were Ben Otaké; Rich Montgomery; Mills Crenshaw; Tom Garriga; Rick Flores; Al and Jim Tracy of Tracy Kenpo; Chuck Sullivan; Mark Georgantas; John McSweeney; and Dave Hebler.In 1962. He was well known in Hollywood, where he trained several stunt men and celebrities—most notably Elvis Presley, to whom he eventually awarded a first-degree black belt in Kenpo. He left behind a few world-renowned grand masters: Al Tracy; Bob White; Richard "Huk" Planas; Larry Tatum; Ron Chapel; and Frank Trejo, who ran a school in California prior to his death. Parker helped Bruce Lee gain national attention by introducing him at his International Karate Championships.

My memorable highlights with Senior G.M. Edmund K. Parker where 1.)When he gave me my I.K.K.A. jacket,2)Watching him promote my Masters to 5th Dan Vic Leroux, 6th Dan George Quinones & 7th Dan Chuck Sullivan,3.)Watching him train my masters at the Santa Monica school, 4.)watching him play the Ukulele at his tribute event,5.)He had me train actress Lauren Tewes while he answered the phone at his Pasadena school and sadly attending his funeral at forest lawn cemetery Glendale, CA. Dec. 22, 1990 #kenpokarate #usa

We had a great moment with Jennifer Lopez, also known as JLO, is an American Singer, Actress, Dancer, Fashion Designer, Author, and Producer. She received her first leading role in the Selena biopic of the same name in 1997, a portrayal that earned her a Golden Globe nomination. With the simultaneous release of her second studio album J.LO and her film The Wedding Planner in 2001, Ms. Lopez became the first woman to have a number one album and film in the same week. Her 2002 remix album, J to the L-O! The Remixes, became the first in history to debut at number one on the U.S. Billboard 200. She subsequently married longtime friend Singer Marc Anthony, and rebounded with the box office successes Shall We Dance? 2004 and Monster-in-Law 2005.One of my favorites El Cantante is a 2006 biographical film which stars Marc Anthony and Jennifer Lopez. The film is based on the life of the late great salsa singer Hector Lavoe. Her fifth studio album, Como Ama Una Mujer 2007, received the highest first week sales for a debut Spanish album in the U.S. Lopez gave birth to twins in 2008, and then in 2011 returned to prominence with her appearance as a judge on American Idol and most commercially successful single to date, "On The Floor", which is one of the best selling singles of all time. In 2016, she began starring as Harlee Santos in the crime drama series Shades of Blue. With a cumulative film gross of over U.S. $2.89 billion and global record sales exceeding 80 million, she is regarded as the most influential Hispanic performer in the U.S. as well as its highest paid Latin entertainer. Lopez received a landmark star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame. Special thanks to Fausto Cuevas III, JLO’s Timbalero & percussionist whom I use to teach his little girls karate. Vivica Anjanetta Fox is an American actress, producer, and television host. Fox began her career on Soul Train (1982–1983). She eventually continued her career with roles on the daytime television soap operas Days of Our Lives (1988) and Generations (1989–1991), subsequently shifting to the prime-time slot, starring opposite Patti LaBelle, in the NBC sitcom Out All Night (1992–1993). Fox's breakthrough came in 1996, with roles in two box-office hit films, Roland Emmerich's Independence Day and F. Gary Gray's Set It Off. 

In the early 1990s, Fox began appearing in prime time television, playing guest-starring roles on The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air, Beverly Hills, 90210, Family Matters, Matlock, and Martin. In 1992, she was cast as Patti LaBelle's fashion-designer daughter, Charisse Chamberlain, on the NBC sitcom Out All Night. In addition to this role, she returned to soap operas, playing the role of Dr. Stephanie Simmons on CBS' The Young and the Restless from 1994 to 1995. In 1995, she also had a cameo role in the comedy film Don't Be a Menace to South Central While Drinking Your Juice in the Hood.

In 1996, Fox played Will Smith's character's girlfriend, Jasmine Dubrow, in the epic science fiction disaster blockbuster Independence Day, directed by Roland Emmerich. The film grossed over $800 million worldwide. Fox received an MTV Movie Award for Best Kiss with Smith, and was nominated for a Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actress. Later that year, she played Francesca "Frankie" Sutton in the crime action film Set It Off opposite Jada Pinkett Smith, Queen Latifah and Kimberly Elise. 

In 2001, Fox played Lucille Slocumb in Kingdom Come, a comedy-drama starring LL Cool J, Jada Pinkett Smith, and Whoopi Goldberg. That same year, she was the lead in the romantic comedy Two Can Play That Game, and had a supporting role in the independent comedy-drama Little Secrets. In 2002, she starred alongside Miguel A. Núñez Jr. in Juwanna Mann and Cuba Gooding Jr. in Boat Trip. Aaron Cohen is a former special operations commando turned celebrity bodyguard, turned actor who has supported opposite Channing Tatum, Nick Cage and Sylvester Stallone. He's a 35-year martial artist and tactical weapons instructor who holds multiple black belts. At the age of 18, Cohen volunteered and was selected to serve in a secret Israeli commando unit operating undercover (in disguise), inside terrorist hotbed territory, designated to infiltrate terrorist cells, (made famous by the hit Netflix show Fauda). Cohen is the only American to have served in the unit. After his service, Cohen returned to Los Angeles spending the next 15 years body-guarding Hollywood's elite including (Brad Pitt, Arnold Schwarzenegger and Kate Moss), while training SWAT teams across the country in active shooter and counter terrorist response. Cohen got his Hollywood start tech advising and training actors in tactical weapons and fighting for film including: Keanu Reeves for John Wick, and then quickly transitioned into acting, getting his first break in Steven Soderbergh's action thriller Haywire, supporting Gina Carano (Mandalorian) and Channing Tatum (Magic Mike). His first major acting role was in the gritty Netflix Cop drama 211 supporting opposite Oscar winner Nick Cage and was recently featured in Rambo 5: Last Blood opposite Sylvester Stallone. Cohen is currently recurring in the hit Netflix Series Luis Miguel, opposite Diego Boneta, and can be seen supporting opposite Antonio Banderas in the action thriller 'The Enforcer' which came out in 2022. 

Thank You Karate Connection Kenpo Karate Brother Cohen for supporting us at the 17th Annual California Youth Karate Nationals, Rose Bowl Stadium, Pasadena, CA. Also, special thanks for connecting us to Dr. Joey Cadena my other Kenpo Brother. 
Mr. Aaron Cohen is pictured with his lovely wife Mrs. Leah Cohen.

PS I Love You Foundation & FABLETICS’
22nd Annual Day at the Beach Was a huge success on the sand of Manhattan Beach between 6th & 8th street where 300 underserved children ages 5-12 from various after-school programs, shelters, and foster care, where united one-on-one with caring adult volunteers for a day of healthy interaction, inclusion, trust building, fun and friendship! They joined relay races, mini golf, boogie boarding, face painting, cupcake making, karate and more. 

Volunteers & Mentors included California Youth Karate Club, Inc., Evolution Academy, Activities run by NCL, Amigos Unidos, Sandpipers, Girl Scouts, Hermanos, MCHS Baseball Team, Boardriders, RAMS Mascot & Cheerleaders , LMU/UCLA.

PS I Love You Foundation, a 501(c)3 established in 1998 and reaching 1,000 youth annually, is dedicated to the development and implementation of effective Social Emotional Learning and Resilience Programs to benefit the overall health and well-being of youth K-12 in our most vulnerable communities.
